          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Ukraine ready to replace Hungary
</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-10-1.png" alt="Ukraine ready to replace Hungary" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Relations between Ukraine and Hungary are becoming more tense. Hungary has increasingly become Moscow-friendly and has expanded Russian gas imports via Turkey, defying EU efforts to reduce its reliance on Russian energy. Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto accused Ukraine of worsening Europe’s energy crisis by ending the gas transit deal with Russia. Ukraine dismissed the claims, stating that the alleged negative impact of the crisis is part of a <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-01-2025-h1-1-politcally-motivated-information-campaign" target="_blank">politically motivated information campaign</a> and added that the EU’s energy security is not threatened. They also mockingly offered to replace Hungary in the EU and NATO if Budapest aligned with Russian-led blocs like the CIS or CSTO.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Kyiv criticized Hungary’s stance as undermining EU unity and asked to focus on its energy security and independence. They also added that Slovakia and Austria were trying to pass on the blame instead of working on their energy problems, which were the 2 of the 27 countries affected by the gas transit deal cancellation. Ukraine also praised the European Commission and governments for the successful <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-01-2025-h1-2-diversification-of-supply" target="_blank">diversification of supply</a> with alternatives from the US and the Middle East.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

 
