          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is the African Union?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-10-3.png" alt="What is the African Union?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The African Union (AU) was launched in 2002, replacing the Organisation of African Unity (OAU), established in 1963 to promote unity and independence across Africa. The <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-01-2025-f1-9-african-union-mission" target="_blank">African Union's mission</a> centers on fostering greater integration, socio-economic development, and peace throughout the continent. Its goals are to promote democracy, human rights, sustainable development, and collaboration with international partners.
</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The AU's structure includes key decision-making bodies, such as the Assembly of Heads of State, the Executive Council, and other specialized committees. Additionally, the AU focuses on regional integration through Economic Communities and aims for long-term transformation through its <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-01-2025-f2-10-agenda-2063-framework" target="_blank">Agenda 2063 framework</a>.
</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The AU is made up of 55 Member States, representing all the countries on the African continent. It is divided into five geographic regions. Morocco was out of the Union for an extended period but rejoined in 2017. There are six members currently on suspension: Gabon, Niger, Guinea, Sudan, Burkina Faso, and Mali.</p>
        </mj-text>
